Case Study 1

Elaine Ji

2019/7/27

Discussion

This is a data set about toys for sale on Amazon, which covers nearly everything that customers can see on Amazons website. In the face of this real and chaotic data set, although there is have no obvious business problems to solve, we can get some inspirations about supplier selection from the data.

The variables in the data set can be divided into three major parts: Product data, Seller data, and Buyer data. These three make up the Amazons data ocean. By analyzing the relationships among the three types of data, we can peek into the connections between buyers and sellers on Amazons website through products.

In addition, I also try to explore the factors that may influence review rating, so as to predict the portrait of Amazons consumer group.

Part 1: Data Cleaning and Wrangling

Initial setup

library(tidyverse)
library(reshape2)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(stringr)

Data Quality and Wrangling

1. Issues

After observing this dataset, I found the following issues:

  • Some variables have characters that we dont need
    e.g.price, average_review_rating

  • One column contains several variables
    e.g.number_available_in_stock, amazon_category_and_sub_category, customer_questions_and_answers, customer_reviews, sellers

  • One row contains several observations
    e.g.customers_who_bought_this_item_also_bought, items_customers_buy_after_viewing_this_item, customer_questions_and_answers, customer_reviews, sellers

  • Two columns have nearly the same informations
    e.g.description, product_description

2. Tidy the data

#Remove null columns
toys <- toys[,-(18:ncol(toys))]  

#Remove needless characters and convert to numeric
toys$price <- as.numeric(substr(toys$price,2,10))  
toys$average_review_rating <- as.numeric(substr(toys$average_review_rating,1,3))

#Separate variables into multiple columns
df <- toys %>%
  separate(amazon_category_and_sub_category,
           into = c("cate1","cate2","cate3","cate4","cate5") ,sep = ">")
df <- df %>%
  separate(number_available_in_stock,into = c("stock_number","stock_status") )

#Count numbers of element and save to new column
df$customer_also_bought_num <-
  str_count(df$customers_who_bought_this_item_also_bought,"http://")
df$customer_viewed_also_bought_num <- 
  str_count(df$items_customers_buy_after_viewing_this_item,"http://")

#Separate observations into multiple rows and save into new datasets
a <- separate_rows(df,customers_who_bought_this_item_also_bought,
                   sep = "\\|",convert = TRUE)
a <- a[,c(1,14)]
b <- separate_rows(df,items_customers_buy_after_viewing_this_item,
                   sep = "\\|",convert = TRUE)
b <- b[,c(1,18)]

#Remove the repetitive variable
df <- df[,-16]

#Separate observations into multiple rows then separate variables into multiple columns. Save into new datasets
c<- separate_rows(df,customer_questions_and_answers,
                  sep = "\\|",convert = TRUE)
c <- c[,c(1,19)]
c <- separate(c,customer_questions_and_answers,
              into = c("question","answer"),sep = "//")

d <- separate_rows(df,customer_reviews,
                   sep = "\\|",convert = TRUE)
d <- d[,c(1,20)]
d <- separate(d,customer_reviews,
              into = c("review_title","review_rating","review_time",
                       "review_name","review_content"), sep = "//")
d$review_name <- substr(d$review_name,14,(nchar(d$review_name)-17))

e <- separate_rows(df,sellers,sep = '"Seller_name_')
w <- grep(pattern = 'seller"=>',e$sellers,ignore.case = FALSE)
e <- e[-w,c(1,21)]
e <- separate(e,sellers,into = c("seller_name","seller_price"),sep = "Seller_price_")
e <- separate(e,seller_name,into=c("1","2","seller_name","4"),sep = '\"')
e <- e[,c(1,4,6)]
e <- separate(e,seller_price,into=c("1","2","seller_price","4"),sep = '\"')
e <- e[,c(1,2,5)]
e$seller_price <- as.numeric(substr(e$seller_price,2,10))

#Merge observations into one row and save it to the summary dataset
customer_questions<- c %>% group_by(uniq_id)%>%
  summarize(question=paste(question,collapse = " | "))
customer_answers<- c %>% group_by(uniq_id)%>%
  summarize(answer=paste(answer,collapse = " | "))
df2<- merge(df,customer_questions)
df2 <- merge(df2,customer_answers)
df2 <- df2[-c(1,2),]

review_titles <-d %>% group_by(uniq_id)%>%
  summarize(review_title=paste(review_title,collapse = " | "))
review_contents <- d %>% group_by(uniq_id)%>%
  summarize(review_content=paste(review_content,collapse = " | "))
df2<- merge(df2,review_titles)
df2 <- merge(df2,review_contents)

sellers_name <- e %>% group_by(uniq_id)%>%
  summarize(seller_name=paste(seller_name,collapse = " | "))
df2<- merge(df2,sellers_name)
df2$stock_number <- as.numeric(paste(df2$stock_number))
df2 <- df2[,c(1:3,10:14,4:9,16,17,22:28,18,15)]

Missing values

In the real world data, missing values are inevitable. It would be too extreme to delete all the missing values. However, its better to use na.rm=TRUE to omit missing values before analysis.

length(which(is.na(df2$manufacturer)))
## [1] 6
length(which(is.na(df2$cate1)))
## [1] 690
length(which(is.na(df2$price)))
## [1] 1454

Part 2: Data Analysis

Product

Product is Amazons blood. Amazon has many kinds of toys, which are presented as category in this data.

What kinds of products have the most brands, the most products, the highest prices, and the most inventory?

#Data Manipulation#
cate_summary <- 
  df2 %>%
    group_by(cate1) %>%
    summarize(Count = n(),Rate=mean(average_review_rating,na.rm = TRUE),Reviews=mean(number_of_reviews,na.rm = TRUE),Answers=mean(number_of_answered_questions,na.rm = TRUE),Stock=mean(stock_number,na.rm = TRUE),Price=mean(price,na.rm = TRUE),Manufacturer=length(levels(factor(manufacturer))))

#Visualization#
#What kinds of toys have most products?
cate_count<- na.exclude(subset(cate_summary,Count>20))
ggplot(data = cate_count, mapping = aes(x = reorder(cate1,Count),y=Count)) +
  geom_col(aes(alpha=Stock),color = "cadetblue4",fill="cadetblue4") +
  labs(x="Category",y="Number of Products",title = "What kinds of toys have most products?") +
  coord_flip()+
  geom_text(label=round(cate_count$Count,2),check_overlap = TRUE,size=2,color="black",hjust=-0.05)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust =0.5, vjust=0.5))

#What kinds of toys have the most brands?
cate_brand<- na.exclude(subset(cate_summary,Manufacturer>15))
ggplot(data = cate_brand, mapping = aes(x = reorder(cate1,Manufacturer),y=Manufacturer,alpha=Stock)) +
  geom_col(fill="cadetblue4",color = "cadetblue4") +
  labs(x="Category",y="Number of Brands",title = "What kinds of toys have the most brands?") +
  coord_flip()+
  geom_text(label=round(cate_brand$Manufacturer,2),check_overlap = TRUE,size=2,color="black",hjust=-0.05)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust =0.5, vjust=0.5))

Seller

If product is Amazons blood, seller would be Amazons blood vessel. There are thousands of toys brands in Amazon, which are presented as manufacturer in this data.

What brands have the widest product lines, the largest number of products, the highest prices, and the largest inventory?

#Data Manipulation#
brand_summary <- 
  df2 %>%
    group_by(manufacturer) %>%
    summarize(Count = n(),Rate=mean(average_review_rating,na.rm = TRUE),Reviews=mean(number_of_reviews,na.rm = TRUE),Answers=mean(number_of_answered_questions,na.rm = TRUE),Stock=mean(stock_number,na.rm = TRUE),Price=mean(price,na.rm = TRUE),Category=length(levels(factor(cate1))))
brand_summary$Review_level <- brand_summary$Reviews*brand_summary$Rate

#Visualiztion#
#What brands are the most dominant?
brand_count<- na.exclude(subset(brand_summary,Count>50))
ggplot(data = brand_count, mapping = aes(x = reorder(manufacturer,Count),y=Count)) +
  geom_col(aes(alpha=Stock),color = "cadetblue4", fill="cadetblue4") +
  labs(x="Brand",y="Number of Products",title = "What brands are the most dominant?") +
  coord_flip()+
  geom_text(label=round(brand_count$Count,2),check_overlap = TRUE,size=2,color="black",hjust=-0.05)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust =0.5, vjust=0.5))

#What brands cover the most categorys?
brand_cate<- na.exclude(subset(brand_summary,Category>5))
ggplot(data = brand_cate, mapping = aes(x = reorder(manufacturer,Category),y=Category,alpha=Stock)) +
  geom_col(fill="cadetblue4",color = "cadetblue4") +
  labs(x="Brand",y="Number of Category",title = "What brands cover the most categorys?") +
  coord_flip()+
  geom_text(label=round(brand_cate$Category,2),check_overlap = TRUE,size=2,color="black",hjust=-0.05)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust =0.5, vjust=0.5))

Buyer

Every interaction of customers on amazons website will leave a footprint, forming valuable data resources of amazon. There are several ways for customers to leave a footprint, including writing reviews, rating, asking questions and answering.

What kinds of products and brands get the best reviews, the most reviews and answered questions?

#What kinds of toys are the most satisfactory?

Part 3: Whats More?

Customer Characteristic

I try to explore the factors that may influence review rating, so as to predict the portrait of Amazons consumer group.

#What are the factors that may influence review rating?
#price x rating
ggplot(data = df2,mapping = aes(x = price,y = average_review_rating)) +
  geom_point(color = "cadetblue4")+
  geom_smooth(color="goldenrod1") +
  labs( x = "Price",y = "Review Rating",
  title = "Do Amazon's customers have price preference in price?") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust =0.5, vjust=0.5))+
  ylim(4,5)+
  xlim(0,750)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Based on this graph, we can see that there is a positive linear relationship between price and review rating. As the price increases, there are hardly any low ratings, making the average rating increases. It may indicate that the Amazons customers are not chasing the low price and have a preference of higher price and good quality.

Additional Data?

There are some key variables that are not offered in this dataset.

  • We have no number of sales. So its hard to tell the popularity.

  • we have no number of questions. We just have number of answered questions. So, we cannot calculate the ratio of the question answering. This ratio can show the attention degree of a particular product.

  • we have no cost of product. We only have the price. So we can not figure out the profit.

Maybe our next step is to collect the missing data above, in order to fulfill the analysis.

Textual and Sentiment Analysis?

There are many character variables in the dataset that I havent analysis at this stage. Variables like customer reviews, customer questions and customer answers have a lot of hidden value, waiting to be discovered by more powerful analytical techniques. I think textual analysis and sentiment analysis are our future tasks.
